ce:section.ce:para:
For DFT, we have selected COOH functionalized coronene (CQD’s) as a model for metal ion adsorption on surface to analyse the optoelectronic properties of the complexes. The optimized geometries of the all the surface functionalized complex models were shown in Fig. 9
                        . In this surface model, all metal ions were strongly adsorbed on carbon CQD surface (i.e C-Mn+ bond) except Ca2+, Mg2+, Cr3+ and Al3+ ions. Particularly Al3+ was not adsorbed on CQD surface whereas other trivalent ion Cr3+ weakly adsorbed. After complexation with metal ion, the Mn+-C bond distance significantly varied from 2.0 to 3.9 Å. The distance higher than the 3.0 Å considered as weakly adsorbed metals. Here, Ca2+ (3.959 Å), Mg2+ (3.768 Å) and Cr3+ (3.770 Å) metal ions were very weekly adsorbed on CQD surface. Whereas other metal ions such as Mn2+, Ni2+, Cu2+ and Zn2+ were strongly bonded with the carbon atom(s) of the CQD surface and the respective bond distances varied from 2.0 to 2.4 Å. It is interesting to note that Ni2+ (2.080 Å) and Cu2+ (∼2.193 Å) formed a very strong bond with surface and other metals such as Co2+ (2.238 Å), Zn2+ (2.348 Å) and Mn2+ (2.386 Å) formed a moderate bond. Further, Cu2+ strongly adsorbed on aromatic CC π-bond, whereas other metals formed σ-bond(s) with the carbon atom (CMn+) and the respective calculated distances are varied from 2.0 to 2.4 Å depending on the metal adsorption site. It was found that CNi2+ bond distance is very strong and shorter bond when compared to the other metal ions. This is also reflected in the binding energies (BEs) of the complexes (shown in Table 2
                        ). Ca2+formed a weakly bond when compared to all the metal ion considered in this study. This is because of the valence shell electronic configuration of the metal cation. The order of stability for the complexes was Ni2+ > Cu2+ > Co2+ > Zn2+ > Mg2+ > Ca2+. The calculated BEs of the complexes was good accordance with the geometrical distance between the complexes. The mode of adsorption and bonding between metal ions and the surface may tune the electronic properties of the complexes. The calculated BEs, HOMO-LUMO gap (Eg), charge of the metal ion on surface and calculated UV-vis adsorption wave length (in nm) are provided in Table 2.
